    The crash occurs due to a use-after-free error caused by invalidating an    
    iterator after a vector reallocation, which happens during push_back when   
    the internal capacity is exceeded.                                          
                                                                                
    Walkthrough of the Program State:                                           
                                                                                
     1 Initial Vector Setup:                                                    
        • std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                    
        • The vector has size() = 4 and an initial capacity() (likely 4 or 5    
          on most implementations).                                             
     2 Iterator Creation:                                                       
        • auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                              
        • This creates an iterator pointing to the third element (v[2] == 3).   
        • At this point, it is valid and refers to the element 3.               
     3 Repeated push_back Calls:                                                
        • The loop runs 1000 times: for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {            
          v.push_back(i); }                                                     
        • Initially, the vector can accommodate a few more elements without     
          reallocation (since capacity ≥ 4).                                    
        • But after the vector exceeds its current capacity, push_back          
          triggers reallocation:                                                
           • A new, larger block of memory is allocated.                        
           • All existing elements are copied (or moved) to the new block.      
           • The old memory block is freed.                                     
           • The iterator it, which points into the old memory, becomes         
             invalid (stale).                                                   
     4 Dereferencing the Stale Iterator:                                        
        • After the loop: std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", *it);     
        • The iterator it now points to memory that has been freed or reused —  
          this is a use-after-free.                                             
        • This triggers AddressSanitizer (ASan) and crashes the program.        
     5 Why Debug Commands Failed:                                               
        • frame variable it and frame variable v failed because it and v are    
          not in scope at the crash point (axiom-of-asan), or because the       
          names may have been optimized or erased in debug symbols.             
        • print v.size() and print v.capacity() failed because they are not     
          valid lldb commands — correct syntax is expression v.size() or print  
          v.size().                                                             
        • However, even if the expressions were allowed, they would not help    
          now — the program crashed before the expression could evaluate.       
     6 Root Cause:                                                              
        • Invalidating an iterator (it) during vector reallocation via          
          push_back, and then dereferencing it afterward.                       
        • This is a well-known C++ pitfall: iterators into a std::vector are    
          invalidated when the vector is reallocated.                           
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Why push_back Causes Reallocation:                                          
                                                                                
     • When v.capacity() is exceeded, push_back reallocates the internal        
       buffer.                                                                  
     • The standard library uses a growth strategy (typically doubling), which  
       means that when size() exceeds the current capacity, reallocation        
       occurs.                                                                  
     • Since the original v started with size() = 4 and capacity() = 4          
       (assume), after ~4–5 more push_backs, reallocation is triggered.         
     • After that, it (which points into the old memory) is no longer valid.    
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Why the it Expression Failed:                                               
                                                                                
    Even though it is logically still in scope, the stack may have been         
    corrupted, or the debugger might not have access to the variable due to     
    ASan's runtime behavior. But the stack trace and code make it clear — the   
    error is not a debugger issue, but a concrete memory safety violation.      
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    ✅ Minimal Local Fix:                                                       
                                                                                
    Replace the use of the invalidated iterator with a direct access or         
    recompute the value after the loop.                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // Fixed version (minimal fix)                                             
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
         auto it = v.begin() + 2;                                               
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         // Instead of *it, which is invalid after reallocation, access the     
     element directly                                                           
         std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", v[2]);  // Safe            
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    ▌ This avoids using the invalid iterator but does not fix the underlying    
    ▌ logic flaw — it just saves the crash.                                     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ✅ Thorough Root-Cause Fix:                                                 
                                                                                
    If the intention was to preserve access to the element at index 2 even      
    after insertions, do not rely on iterators. Instead:                        
                                                                                
     • Store the value (or position) before modifying the vector.               
     • Or, do not modify the vector if you need to preserve iterator validity.  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
         std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};                                     
                                                                                
         // Store the value you care about before any modifications             
         int expected_value = v[2];  // This is 3                               
                                                                                
         for (int i = 0; i < 1000; ++i) {                                       
             v.push_back(i);                                                    
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         std::printf("element via stale iter: %d\n", expected_value);  //       
     Safe and correct                                                           
         return 0;                                                              
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    ▌ This is resilient to reallocation, and clearly communicates intent.       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Summary                                                                     
                                                                                
     • Root Cause: Iterator it is invalidated by vector reallocation during     
       push_back, then dereferenced.                                            
     • Data Corrupt: The memory pointed to by it was freed.                     
     • Fix: Never use iterators from a vector after operations that may         
       reallocate—especially push_back when capacity is exceeded.               
     • Best Practice: Use indices (v[i]) or store values instead of relying on  
       iterators across modifications.                                          
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Fix: Replace *it with v[2] or store the value before the loop.           
     2 Improve: Avoid using iterators across push_back operations when          
       capacity may be exceeded. Prefer indices or value storage for            
       persistent access.                                                       
     3 Prevent: Use reserve(n) if you know the final size — this avoids         
